{"author":{"id":"4bb6c1767e50694cfde61856db22bf137d1651e8a0b5ca858c486db3dd02f280"},"ops":[{"type":3,"timestamp":1774290819,"nonce":"tKlf3oPQ6oT+bizOcTzcXFbefBA=","message":"## Additional Gemini perspectives (independent analysis — did not see Opus deep-dive)\n\nGemini produced an independent critique by examining the codebase directly. Key additional points:\n\n1. **Cleaner separation than continuum suggests**: Gemini argues the distinction CAN be cut more cleanly via Jacobian analysis — robustness scales the feedback Jacobian (∂u/∂y changes magnitude), while adaptation shifts fixed-point locations in a direction that \"cancels\" the perturbing vector. This is a useful operational distinction even if the underlying computation is continuous.\n\n2. **SISU-adaptation confound**: If the network learns u ≈ SISU · sgn(error), this looks like adaptation but is actually nonlinear gain-scheduled robust control. The direction-reversal probe is the cleanest way to resolve this.\n\n3. **Timescale separation**: Adaptation implies changes to the internal model (plant representation); robustness implies changes to the feedback policy (y → u mapping). In the RNN, these may overlap, but the *timescale* of the policy shift within a trial could distinguish them — adaptation requires estimation time, robustness is immediate conditioned on SISU.\n\n4. **Simpler ceiling approach**: Instead of oracle retraining, use loss sensitivity analysis — measure ∂Loss/∂σ_perturb as a function of training σ. A ceiling is reached when increasing training intensity no longer reduces evaluation sensitivity.\n\n5. **Effective dimensionality**: Check whether the \"robust\" regime (high SISU) occupies a larger RNN state-space subspace. Robustness may require more redundant representations to maintain stability.\n\n6. **Priority ranking differs from Opus**: Gemini ranks direction-reversal highest (behavioral disambiguation), then steady-state Jacobian eigenspectra (mechanistic confirmation), with MI decomposition lower (likely too noisy for reliable estimation from RNN hidden states).\n\nCo-authored-by: Gemini 3.1 Pro Preview \u003cnoreply@google.com\u003e","files":null}]}